# GOI GIS Tool — HTML Architecture Guardrails

## Canonical file / scope
- The canonical app lives in a **single** HTML file (currently: `coordinate_converter Claude.html`).
- Keep changes surgical and consistent with the existing patterns in that file.

## State, persistence, and invariants
- Centralized app state object: `state`.
- Persistence via localStorage key: `coordconv_v2` (bumped from `coordconv_v1` during the pre-GIS cleanup; the old v1 key is intentionally ignored, not actively wiped).
- GIS Phase 1 data model is additive and hybrid:
  - `state.mapWaypoints[]` remains the canonical waypoint store (cap 200).
  - `state.track` remains the legacy draft track builder.
  - `state.gisTracks[]` (cap 50), `state.gisPolygons[]` (cap 50), and `state.gisLayers[]` (cap 20) are persisted GeoJSON-native stores for future GIS features.
  - `state.gisSelection`, `state.undoStack`, and `state.redoStack` are transient; undo/redo is scaffolded but has no UI/shortcut activation in Phase 1.
  - `gisAllAsFeatureCollection()` is the read-lens that emits a GeoJSON FeatureCollection across existing waypoints plus GIS tracks/polygons.
- IndexedDB is used for offline map tile pack and some geo caches.
- On load, persisted data must be **sanitized/clamped** (numbers, string length, arrays caps). Do not trust localStorage content.

## Map + offline behavior
- The mini-map must be usable even with no active conversion:
  - Default startup center is **La Spezia** fallback (no silent GPS at startup).
- Offline behavior:
  - When effectively offline, prefer rendering cached tiles from IndexedDB and show placeholders for missing tiles.
  - Do not introduce an automatic “online fallback” that defeats the user’s offline/OPSEC choices.

## Geolocation UX (opt-in only)
- Geolocation must be **explicit opt-in** via UI actions (no automatic `getCurrentPosition()` on page load).
- Respect secure context constraints (`window.isSecureContext`): if not secure, disable geo UI and explain why.
- Single-shot only: `btnMyLocation` uses `getCurrentPosition`. Continuous tracking via `watchPosition` has been removed (pre-GIS cleanup).

## Rendering and history
- `renderResults(lat, lon, meta, opts)` supports an option like `{ skipHistory: true }` used for:
  - language re-apply / UI rerender that must not duplicate history

## i18n
- i18n dictionary exists inline (IT/EN/FR).
- There is both:
  - `data-i18n` → updates via `textContent` (default, safe)
  - `data-i18n-html` → updates via `innerHTML` (only for explicitly allowed rich-text help content)
- Do not expand `innerHTML` usage beyond the intended rich-text areas.

## Event handlers / cleanup
- Handlers for map tools (bbox draw, draggable panels, pick modes) are designed to be **idempotent** (install once) and provide explicit cleanup on cancel/Esc.
- Do not add listeners in hot paths without a cleanup plan.

## GIS viewer/planner layout (current default)
- The app boots in **GIS mode** (`<body class="gis-mode">`). Layout:
  - Compact `<header>` (brand + settings/theme/print/help/Strumenti).
  - `<nav id="appTopbar">`: tab buttons (`track`, `waypoints`, `measure`, `favorites`, `geocoding`, `history`, `layers`), CTA **Converti**, kebab **Altri strumenti**.
  - `<main>` only hosts `<div id="gisMapMount">` (the map fills the viewport); classic homepage cards (`#pasteSection`, `#manualInputSection`, `#geocodeCard`, `.grid`, `#toolsCollapsible`) are hidden via `body.gis-mode > main > …` selectors.
- Tab activation **reparents** the target `<details>` into `<aside id="tabDrawer">` via `appendChild` (no clone). `GIS_HOME_SLOTS` caches the original parent+nextSibling so `deactivateTab()` restores the section verbatim. Summaries are hidden inside the drawer; the drawer header supplies the title.
- Convert modal (`<dialog id="convertModal">`) reparents the classic conversion cards (paste / manual input / `#geocodeCard` / `.results-col`) on open and restores them on close. The geocoding card is skipped if the `geocoding` tab is active.
- Altri strumenti modal (`<dialog id="toolsModal">`) hosts Batch / Note / Sessione / Astro / Mag via the same reparenting pattern (section id ↔ tile button).
- Esc is wired at document level to close modals/drawer in that order.
- The on-map coverage button is intercepted in capture phase: in GIS mode it activates the `layers` tab (so the user sees `#offlineTilePanel` in context) instead of toggling a hidden home slot.
- Layout persistence: `state.gisMode` and `state.activeTab` (whitelist: `GIS_VALID_TABS`) are saved across sessions; `convertOpen` and `toolsMenuOpen` are transient.

## Section ids required by the GIS hub
- Tabs: `sec-track`, `sec-waypoints`, `sec-measure`, `sec-favorites`, `geocodeCard`, `sec-history`, `offlineTilePanel`.
- Tools modal: `sec-batch`, `sec-notes`, `sec-session`, `sec-astro`, `sec-mag`.
- The manual-input section wrapper must carry `id="manualInputSection"` (used by both the home-hide CSS and the Convert modal reparenting).
- The map root `#miniMap` is reparented once at init into `#gisMapMount`; rendering code queries by id, so this is transparent.

## Tab-as-modal pattern (waypoints + track)
- Some tools open as a dedicated `<dialog class="app-modal">` instead of the side drawer. **Waypoints:** `openWaypointModal()` reparents `sec-waypoints` into `#waypointModalBody`. **Track (GIS):** `openTrackModal()` reparents `sec-track` into `#trackModalBody` (builder + saved-track archive). The map toolbar toggles call these openers/closers; `GIS_VALID_TABS` excludes both `waypoints` and `track` so they never use `#tabDrawer`.
- `deactivateTab()` only restores drawer-hosted sections. Modal sections restore via `closeWaypointModal()` / `closeTrackModal()` (`gisRestoreSection`).
- Persistence: `state.activeTab === "waypoints"` is still saved for the waypoint topbar pill; track is not a topbar tab — legacy saves with `activeTab === "track"` reopen the track modal once via `state._pendingTrackModal`. `state.waypointsModalOpen`, `state.trackModalOpen`, and editor/draft flags are transient (not persisted), same pattern as `state.convertOpen` / `state.toolsMenuOpen`.
- The Waypoints modal reuses `state.mapWaypoints` and the same on-map pick flow (`state.waypointPickMode`, `state.trackWaypointDraft`) as before. Do not duplicate these arrays or add a second click handler on the map.
- Saved track archive: `state.savedTracks[]` (cap 50, persisted) holds snapshots `{ id, name, savedAt, closed, visible, points }`; visible entries render under the draft overlay as read-only dashed lines.

## GIS & tools UI/UX standards (vincolo operativo)

**Scope:** ogni **nuovo** o **esteso in modo sostanziale** modal `<dialog>`, pannello GIS (drawer, floating, sezione in Strumenti), **tabella operativa** a più colonne, o strumento con interazione **map-first** — salvo deroga esplicita nel prompt o vincolo tecnico documentato.

**Check (Cursor, prima di progettare o implementare la UI):** elenco sotto; deve essere considerato **attivamente** e non come suggerimento generico.

### 1) Tabelle operative in modal / pannelli

Quando la tabella mostra **più colonne** e dati **variabili** o testo potenzialmente lungo (nome, descrizione, centro, coordinate, stato, note, elenchi, ecc.):

- Prevedere **ridimensionamento orizzontale delle colonne** interessate (drag su header o pattern già usato nel monolite, es. *saved tracks* / tabelle con handle), salvo **motivo tecnico esplicito** (es. tabella a una colonna, card-list senza griglia, vincolo mobile assoluto temporaneo).
- Impostare **min-width** / `clamp` così che colonne e sticky header restino usabili.
- **Non** rompere: sticky header, checkbox/selezione, **batch toolbar** sopra o sotto la tabella, **scroll** interno del corpo tabella, layout mobile / overflow.
- Preferire persistenza **transiente** della larghezza in **sessione** o su `state` / nodo mount (come pattern esistenti), coerente con il resto del file. **Niente `localStorage` dedicato alle larghezze colonne** salvo **decisione esplicita** del team.
- **Riutilizzare** classi, handler e convenzioni già presenti nel monolitico invece di introdurre un nuovo sistema ad ogni feature.

Ogni **nuova** tabella operativa del tipo sopra va progettata partendo da questo standard.

### 2) Input tecnici e valori ricorrenti

Quando uno strumento espone input tecnici (distanze, elenchi numerici, opzioni di export, parametri di area, ecc.) con **valori o combinazioni frequenti**:

- Offrire **preset rapidi** (pulsanti *chip* / *btn-sm* vicino al campo) che **compilano o suggeriscono** il valore nel relativo input.
- L’utente deve **sempre** poter **modificare manualmente** l’input dopo un preset; il preset **non** sostituisce la casella editabile.
- Preset **compatti**, non invasivi, visivamente associati al campo. Testo visibile dei preset: **i18n IT/EN/FR** (`data-i18n` o chiavi coerenti).
- Evitare cambi a parser, schema `state` o regole di sanitize **oltre il minimo** necessario per precompilare.

Esempi indicativi (non esaustivi): Range Rings (distanze), scelte export/import, pannello offline (zoom / area) quando opportuno.

### 3) Strumenti map-first

Per strumenti il cui senso operativo è **sulla mappa** (pick punto, aree, traccia, anelli, misura, ecc.):

- Il percorso **primario** deve partire dalla **mappa** quando fattibile: CTA/azione principale **evidente** e orientata alla mappa.
- Input manuale (coordinate, testo) resta **secondario** ma accessibile nello stesso flusso.
- Rispettare invariati: **nessun** GPS all’avvio, **nessuna** `watchPosition`, nessuna rete/Geo **silenziosa** — come da §*Geolocation* / *Map + offline* in questo file e da [`.cursor/rules/00-project-core.mdc`](00-project-core.mdc) (OPSEC, offline-first).

### 4) Coerenza pulsanti in modal e pannelli

- **Primary** (`.btn-primary` o un solo CTA visivamente dominante): solo per l’**azione primaria reale** del pannello (es. *Crea*, *Applica*, *Converti* nel proprio contesto se è davvero il passo unico atteso). Non «blu ovunque».
- **Secondari**: azioni normali (`.btn` / stile secondario) per conferme non finali, navigazione interna, *Salva* secondario.
- **Danger**: eliminazione, reset distruttivo, *clear* irreversibile (classi *danger* / *btn-danger-subtle* già usate).
- **Ghost / subtle / link**: chiusure, *Annulla*, utility, opzioni leggere.
- **Contenuto e azioni principali** in alto; **opzioni**, toggle avanzati, *danger zone* in **basso** o in sezioni secondarie, salvo pattern esistente strutturato diversamente.
